multia annia post] 184 years. C. Hostilius Mancinus was consul rac. 137 with M. Aemilius Lepidus Porcina and had the conduct of the war against Numantia. Being defeated by the enemy he negotiated a peace through the intervention of his quaestor Tib. Gracchus, but the senate refused to recognise it and delivered the consul over to the enemy by means of the fetiales. This was done with the consent of Man· cinus, but the enemy refused toaccept him. On his return to Rome Mancinus took his seat in the senate, as heretofore, but was expelled violently from it by the tribune P. Rutilius, on the ground that he had lost his citizenship. His civic rights were restored to him by a special lex (dig. 50 tit. 7 5 17). Appian de reb. Hispan. 79-83‚ Valer. Max. 165 7, Vell. Patercn 1, Cic. de orat. 1 5 181‚5 138, 11 5 137, pro Caec. 5 98.
